                    <head>Missal, secular use of Linköping diocese</head>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support>
                                    <p>
                                        <locusGrp>
                                            <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                            <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                        </locusGrp>
                                        <material>Parchment</material>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                        <material>Western paper</material>
                                        <note>The paste-down is modern and glued on top of the original parchment paste-down, covering about two-thirds of it.</note>
                                    </p>
                                </support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure type="leftFlyleaves" quantity="0" unit="folios"/>
                                    <measure type="rightFlyleaves" quantity="0" unit="folios"/>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation>Modern foliation in pencil 1-37, 37a-123.</foliation>
                                <collation>
                                    <formula>1(6, lacks 1-3), 2-4(10), 5(9+1), 6-8(10), 9(12), 10(12, lacks 6-7), 11(10+1+2), 12(12, lacks 7-12), 13(10), 14(8, all lacking) </formula>
                                    <p>
                                        <ref target="https://vceditor.library.upenn.edu/project/65523e0bddee9c000197c36c/viewOnly">VisColl collation</ref>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>Collation for quires 5, 11 and 12 is tentative. Parchment guards in all quires, a few of them from fragmented manuscripts. Quires 1 and 12 are mutilated and repaired. In quire 10 one bifolium is lost between <locus from="89" to="89" scheme="folios"/> and <locus from="90" to="90" scheme="folios"/>. Quire 11 is a quinion with one extra leaf and one bifolium. Between quires 12 and 13 an unknown number of quires is missing. After quire 14 several quires are missing.</p>
                                </collation>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>On the original parchment paste down is written in black ink in a late medieval hand: <quote xml:lang="non-swe">
                                        <unclear unit="chars" atLeast="2" atMost="4" reason="illegible"/> bekienner jak karl hanson hawa anamath aff skinberga ena klockio som vogh ett skeppund ok iv lispund oc v marker medh kleppen </quote>. Top left corner: National Library modern book label with the current signum in black ink. Top centre in black ink by an 18-century hand: <quote>No. 58 Brocmanniana Missale Lincopense</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Late medieval and early modern pen trials in black ink by many hands.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding>
                                <p>Late medieval binding. Dark brown leather over wooden boards. Four double raised bands and two endbands. Three clasps. On <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> a modern leather label stamped in gold: <quote>Missale Lincopense M S C</quote>; and below: <quote>A 97</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="295" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="225" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="60" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, blind tooling filled in with red. Double lines creating a centre panel, which is divided by double lines horisontally, vertically and diagonally. Probably the same decoration on the <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather is heavily worn and and cracking along the spine. Leather is torn on the outer corners showing the boards and a large piece is missing on the <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>. Decoration on <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/> is barely visible. Clasps are missing leaving only the brass nails or holes for the nails. A small piece of the wooden board is missing on the outer edge of the <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/> from where the middle clasp was fitted. Remains of a blue (silk?) ribbon glued to the <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/> and thread through a hole in the board to the <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100081">Sweden</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1451">second half of the 15th century</origDate> proposed in <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107245">Lindberg (1923)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="38" to="38" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl> and supported by the watermarks. <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/101006">Helander (1957)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="90" to="90" unit="page"/>
                                    <citedRange from="9" to="9" unit="footnote"/>
                                </bibl> discusses dating based on the calendar and suggests between <date from="1436" to="1441">1436–1441</date>/8.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The mention of <quote xml:lang="sv">Skönberga</quote> in the note on the <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>, recovered by reagent in 1919, could suggest that the missal once belonged to the Church of Skönberga, <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100115">Östergötland</placeName> diocese, as proposed in <bibl>
                                    <title ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107245">Lindberg</title>
                                    <citedRange from="37" to="37" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>: <quote>
                                    <unclear unit="chars" atLeast="2" atMost="4" reason="illegible"/> bekienner jak karl hanson hawa anamath aff skinberga ena klockio som vogh ett skeppund ok iv lispund oc v marker medh kleppen </quote>. One Karl Hansson is recorded as a merchant in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100236">Söderköping</placeName> who in <date when="1532"/> sent a copper bell to <placeName ref="Lü">Lübeck</placeName>, see <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107246">Källström (1939)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="44" to="44" unit="page"/>
                                    <citedRange from="6" to="6" unit="footnote"/>
                                </bibl>. Doubts regarding this provenance are raised in <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107249">Kroon (1951)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="11" to="13" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The missal can also be connected with Västra Sten church, no longer standing, in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100237">Västra stenby socken</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100046">Linköping</placeName> diocese, since Matthias Olavi Dingtunensis, a priest from <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100235">Dingtuna</placeName> in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100116">Västmanland</placeName> (d. <date when="1608"/>), who officiated there in <date from="1579" to="1608">1579-1608 </date>has made an obit entry in the calendar for September 12, <date when="1575"/>, <locus from="2r" to="2r" scheme="folios"/>, for his daughter, see Additions and <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107249">Kroon (1951)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="11" to="13" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The name in the addition on <locus from="4r" to="4r" scheme="folios"/>, now almost completely obliterated but quoted in <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107245">Lindberg (1923)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="37" to="37" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl> as <quote xml:lang="la">Ex libris Bothvidi A nat. salvat. (1)624</quote>, could possibly refer to Bothvid Claudii Pallinaerus, son of the priest in Skönberga church Claudius Bothvidi (<date from="1599" to="1636">1599–1636</date>), student at <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100011">Uppsala University</orgName> in <date when="1625"/>, and district judge (<foreign xml:lang="sv">häradshövding</foreign>) in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100238">Bohuslän</placeName>, see <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107250">Linköpings stifts herdaminne, vol. 3</title>
                                    <citedRange from="538" to="538" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The missal belonged to <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100536">Nils Reinhold Brocman</persName> (<date from="1731" to="1770">1731–1770</date>), librarian at the Royal Library and antiquarian at the Antiquities Archive, see addition on <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>: <quote xml:lang="la">No. 58 Brocmanniana Missale Lincopense</quote>. Brocman bequeathed the manuscript to the Antiquities Archive <date when="1770"/>, see transcription of his will from 1770 in U 89, where it is listed as <quote xml:lang="la">Liturgica in Folio. Missale Lincopense Msct</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>From the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName> to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">Royal Library</orgName>. Brocman's books are registered in the 19th-century inventory U 165:2: <quote xml:lang="sv">I Salongs soubassementerne. Skåpet 13 Brocmanniana.</quote>
                            </p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
